<h2>Solar Panels in Pennsylvania</h2>
<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Pennsylvania receives substantial solar irradiance throughout the year, with peak production occurring during the summer months when air conditioning demands are highest. The state averages 3.9 peak sun hours daily, with southern regions like Philadelphia and Chester County receiving slightly higher irradiance levels than northern areas. During summer months, Pennsylvania can achieve up to 5.5 peak sun hours per day, while winter months typically see 2.5-3.0 peak sun hours daily. This seasonal variation aligns well with energy consumption patterns, as higher solar production coincides with increased cooling needs.</p>

<p>A typical 6kW residential solar system in Pennsylvania can generate approximately 7,200-8,400 kWh annually, which covers 60-80% of average household electricity consumption. The state's moderate climate means that solar panels operate efficiently throughout most of the year, as extreme heat can actually reduce panel efficiency. Pennsylvania's occasional snow cover during winter months has minimal impact on annual production, as panels typically shed snow quickly and the reflection from snow can actually boost production on clear winter days.</p>

<p>Geographic variations within Pennsylvania affect solar production potential, with southeastern regions around Philadelphia typically seeing 5-8% higher production than northwestern areas near Lake Erie. However, even the lowest-producing regions of Pennsylvania still receive enough solar irradiance to make solar installations financially viable, especially when combined with the state's favorable net metering policies and incentive programs.</p>

